The paper deals with distributed computing, specifically in the LOCAL model, which falls under the category of Distributed, Parallel, and Cluster Computing (cs.DC). The paper also discusses the time-complexity of algorithms on graphs, which is a topic in the sub-category of Data Structures and Algorithms (cs.DS). The use of randomized algorithms and the analysis of their expected time-complexity suggest that the paper may also belong to the sub-category of Information Theory (cs.IT). The study of the node-averaged time-complexity and ID-averaged time-complexity may also fall under the sub-categories of Network Economics (cs.NE) and Social and Information Networks (cs.SI), respectively.
